Drawing nice sampling map with climatic data

Nhu L.T. Tran

2025-04-04

  • Load the data
  • Load the necessary libraries
  • Download the bioclimatic data
  • Plot your sampling points without any bioclimatic variables
  • Plot your sampling points with bioclimatic variables

Load the necessary libraries

library(ggplot2) # for plotting
library(raster) # for handling raster data
library(sf) # for handling spatial data
library(rnaturalearth) # for the base map
library(rnaturalearthdata) # for the base map
library(ggspatial) # for scale bar and north arrow in the plot
library(geodata) # for downloading bioclimatic data
library(RColorBrewer) # for aesthetics

Download the bioclimatic data

biocur = worldclim_global(var = "bio", res = 10, data_path2)

We see the “names” are “wc2.1~bio_1”, “wc2.1~bio_2” etc., corresponding to “bio1”, “bio2” and so on.

We rename it for the sake of clarity And then we extract only the European part for memory efficiency

bio = sprintf("bio%d", 1:19) # print bio1 - bio19 characters
names(biocur) = bio # replace these names in the biocur object

# Define coordinate of the Europe range, covering Scandinavia and Caspian
eu_ext = c(-10, 50, 35, 70) 
# Crop the data 
biocur = crop(biocur, eu_ext) 

# See what we have now

Now we can extract the bioclimatic variable of interest

bio9 = biocur[[9]]
# we can also see how it looks like
bio9
## class      : RasterLayer 
## dimensions : 210, 360, 75600  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution : 0.1666667, 0.1666667  (x, y)
## extent     : -10, 50, 35, 70  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## crs        : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs 
## source     : memory
## names      : bio9 
## values     : -14.89104, 35.24166  (min, max)

Then we convert this raster to data.frame for ggplot

bio9_df = as.data.frame(rasterToPoints(bio9))
colnames(bio9_df) = c("Longitude", "Latitude", "BIO9")

Make European country layer

eu = ne_countries(scale = "medium", continent = "europe", returnclass = "sf")

Plot your sampling points without any bioclimatic variables

map = ggplot(data = eu)+
  geom_sf(inherit.aes = T) +
  geom_point(data=df,aes(x=Longitude,y=Latitude),pch=20,
             fill="green4",col="green4",size=2)+
  ##name axes
  labs(title="Sampling sets of 390 accessions")+
  xlab("Longitude") + ylab("Latitude")+
  ##set font size
  theme(axis.text=element_text(size=10),
        axis.title=element_text(size=10))+
  ##Insert compass and scale
  annotation_scale(location = "bl", width_hint = 0.5) + #set the map scale
  annotation_north_arrow( 
    location = "br", which_north = "true", 
    pad_x = unit(0.3, "cm"), pad_y = unit(0.3, "cm"),
    style = north_arrow_fancy_orienteering) + #set the compass, locations can be br, bl, tr, or tl
  #set map limits
  xlim(-10,40) + #longitude range
  ylim(34,70) + #latitude range
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_line(color = gray(.5), 
                                        linetype = "dashed", size = 0.5), 
        panel.background = element_rect(fill = "aliceblue")) +
  theme(plot.title=element_text(family = "Lucida Grande", face = "bold", size=13,hjust=0.5,vjust=1), 
        axis.title.y = element_text(colour = 'black',  size = 11, family = "Lucida Grande", angle=90), 
        axis.title.x = element_text(colour = "black", size = 11, family = "Lucida Grande"),
        axis.text.x = element_text(colour = "black", size = 11, family = "Lucida Grande"),
        axis.text.y = element_text(colour = "black", size = 11, family = "Lucida Grande"),
        legend.title = element_text(colour = "black", size = 11, family = "Lucida Grande"),
        legend.text = element_text(colour = "black", size = 11, family = "Lucida Grande"),
        #plot.background = element_rect(fill = "#C5D6AF")
  )

map

Plot your sampling points with bioclimatic variables

map_combined = ggplot() +
  # Background: raster
  geom_raster(data = bio9_df, aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude, fill = BIO9)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(option = "C", name = "BIO9", na.value = NA) +
  
  # Overlay country borders
  geom_sf(data = eu, fill = NA, color = "gray30", size = 0.3) +
  
  # Sampling points
  geom_point(data = df, aes(x = Longitude, y = Latitude),
             pch = 21, fill = "green4", color = "black", size = 2) +
  
  # Add scale bar and north arrow
  annotation_scale(location = "bl", width_hint = 0.5) +
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "br", which_north = "true",
                         pad_x = unit(0.3, "cm"), pad_y = unit(0.3, "cm"),
                         style = north_arrow_fancy_orienteering) +
  
  # Map limits
  coord_sf(xlim = c(-10, 40), ylim = c(34, 70), expand = FALSE) +
  
  # Theme
  theme_minimal(base_family = "Lucida Grande") +
  labs(title = "Sampling Map with BIO9 Background",
       x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 13, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
        legend.position = "right")

# Show map
map_combined
